Benchmark:

```json
{
  "name": "ltzglue",
  "full_name": "LTZGLUE: The First Natural Language Understanding Benchmark for Luxembourgish",
  "year": 2025,
  "domain": "Natural Language Understanding for Luxembourgish",
  "porting_strategy": "mixed",
  "languages": [
    "lb"
  ],
  "primary_region": "Luxembourg",
  "description": "LTZGLUE is the first unified GLUE-style NLU benchmark for Luxembourgish (LTZ), comprising\neight tasks across binary and multi-class classification settings including headline\nacceptability, sentiment analysis, linguistic acceptability (binary and multi-class), named\nentity recognition, news topic classification, intent detection, and recognizing textual\nentailment. The benchmark combines newly constructed tasks, human-translated adaptations,\nmachine-translated and LLM-refined datasets, and reused existing LTZ corpora. It evaluates\nboth supervised encoder-based models and zero-shot prompted LLMs, and contributes two new\nLTZ-specific encoder models (LTZ-E1-mini and LTZ-E1-base).\n",
  "documentation_excerpts": "## Key characteristics relevant to validity analysis:\n\n### Input Ontology\nLTZGLUE covers eight tasks — headline acceptability (HA), sentiment analysis (SA), linguistic\nacceptability in binary and multi-class forms (LA-BINARY, LA-MULTI), named entity recognition\n(NER), news topic classification (TC), intent detection (ID), and recognizing textual entailment\n(RTE) — explicitly modelled on the English GLUE benchmark [Q1, Q8, Q68]. The suite is designed\nto span \"a broad spectrum of linguistic and semantic phenomena\" [Q11] and covers \"fundamentally\ndifferent modelling paradigms\" [Q71]. Appendix prompts enumerate exact label sets per task\n[Q143–Q155], confirming that all eight tasks emit single hard labels with fixed category sets.\n\nFor the deployment use case, the input ontology presents critical gaps. The topic classification\ntask covers only five editorial categories — SPORTS, CULTURE, TECHNOLOGY, BUSINESS, and\nANIMALS — derived from RTL news [Q48, Q153], with no administrative, civic, housing,\ncross-border worker, EU-institutional, or state-vs-communal competency categories. The intent\ndetection task covers a narrow set of reminder and alarm intents from a voice-assistant corpus\n[Q51, Q154], with no citizen-government communication intents. The NER task retains only four\nentity types (PER, ORG, LOC, MISC) after tag harmonisation [Q44, Q152], with no administrative\njurisdiction or legal-status categories. Topic classification is reported as the easiest task\nwith near-encoder-level LLM performance [Q99, Q100], while RTE is the hardest [Q103] — a\ndifficulty distribution not calibrated to administratively relevant language understanding.\nThe authors acknowledge these structural limitations: \"Coverage across domains, registers, and\ndemographic varieties may also be limited\" [Q112].\n\n### Input Content\nThe benchmark draws primarily on two main text sources: RTL (a Luxembourgish media outlet)\nand the Luxembourgish Online Dictionary (LOD) [Q12], supplemented by Wikipedia, Leipzig\nCollection web crawls, transcribed podcasts, transcribed political speeches from the Chambre\ndes Députés, and Luxembourgish chat rooms [Q74, Q135]. The sentiment analysis data comes from\nRTL commentary and letters to the editor [Q24]; NER merges an automatically constructed\nWikipedia/Wikidata corpus (JUDGEWEL) [Q34, Q38] with a human-annotated RTL news comment\ncorpus [Q40, Q45]; topic classification is drawn from RTL editorial content [Q46]; and the\nintent detection task is a human-translated adaptation of the English xSID dataset [Q51], with\na machine-translated German training set [Q54].\n\nFor the deployment, this source profile is a serious validity concern. The authors explicitly\nacknowledge that \"most data sources reflect formal writing or institutional usage and therefore\ndo not fully represent informal and multilingual contexts\" [Q112], and that \"linguistic data\noften originate from a limited set of public domains\" [Q119]. The intent detection register —\nuser commands for a voice-controlled AI assistant — is acknowledged to have \"no equivalent\nreference corpus in LTZ,\" making systematic terminology verification impossible [Q55, Q56].\nCode-switched, orthographically variable citizen correspondence — the primary input type in\nthe deployment — is absent from nearly all task datasets. The RTE dataset was processed\nthrough ChatGPT-5.1 for quality improvement and then filtered, removing 22–28% of instances\n[Q60, Q66], introducing model-induced distributional artefacts into the content. The\nconstruction required \"a deliberately resource-conscious approach\" combining reuse, targeted\nannotation, and LLM assistance [Q109], reflecting structural constraints of the low-resource\nsetting rather than principled domain selection.\n\n### Input Form\nAll benchmark tasks use plain text inputs in the Luxembourgish language, at sentence or\ndocument level, with BIO-tagged token sequences for NER and intent detection [Q35, Q57].\nThe benchmark explicitly targets Luxembourgish as the input language [Q1], and the pre-training\ntokenizer is a BPE tokenizer trained on the full LTZ pre-training set with a vocabulary of\n50,368 tokens and a maximum sequence length of 1,024 [Q128, Q129]. Non-Luxembourgish articles\nwere filtered using the OpenLID language identifier [Q47], and sentences with fewer than three\nwords were removed [Q75].\n\nFor the deployment, the input form dimension is partially valid: the benchmark is text-based\nand targets Luxembourgish, matching the deployment's text-only modality. However, the\nbenchmark's text form reflects formal, edited prose from news and institutional sources, with\nno documented coverage of non-standard orthography, code-switching with French or German, or\nloanword alternation — all confirmed features of the target deployment's actual input\ndistribution [Q7, Q112]. The authors flag \"ongoing standardisation of the language\" and \"vast\namounts of variation\" as evaluation challenges [Q7], but the benchmark's preprocessing does\nnot address these properties. The intent detection source register further diverges from\ncitizen-correspondence form, using non-standard spelling conventions (all lowercase, missing\npunctuation) that were difficult to render in LTZ [Q55].\n\n### Output Ontology\nThe label ontology across all LTZGLUE tasks is entirely single-label and hard-classification\n[Q84]. Binary tasks use True/False or 0/1 encodings [Q147, Q148, Q150, Q155]. Multi-class\ntasks include three-class sentiment (positive, neutral, negative) [Q149], five-class linguistic\nacceptability (correct, verb, adj, syntax, ortho) [Q151], five-class topic classification\n(sports, culture, technology, business, animals) [Q153], a fixed set of reminder/alarm intents\n[Q154], and BIO NER tags covering LOC, PER, DATE, ORG, and MISC [Q152]. The benchmark did not\nuse a multiple choice question answering setup, instead providing explicit label sets for output\n[Q84].\n\nFor the deployment, the output ontology presents three critical misalignments. First, there\nare no administrative, housing, cross-border worker, civic, or EU-institutional categories in\nany task taxonomy. Second, all tasks emit single hard labels, whereas the deployment requires\nmulti-label outputs with calibrated confidence scores for routing — the benchmark produces no\nprobabilistic or ranked outputs. Third, the sentiment labels (positive/neutral/negative) are\ngeneric and not calibrated to the formal-but-understated register of citizen-government\ncorrespondence. The NER tag set was simplified by merging GPE and LOC into a single location\nlabel [Q44], further reducing the administrative granularity available. The authors caution\nagainst using \"benchmark performance as evidence of cultural or demographic coverage\" [Q121]\nand advise inspecting task-specific subsets before deployment in public-facing settings [Q123].\n\n### Output Content\nAnnotation practices vary substantially across tasks. The sentiment analysis task was annotated\nby two native speakers of Luxembourgish [Q25], instructed to use an \"unsure\" category only\nwhen they would otherwise assign labels randomly [Q26], yielding a Cohen's Kappa of 0.45 [Q27],\nwith disagreements resolved by annotator consensus [Q28]. The intent detection dataset was\ntranslated by a single native LTZ speaker with consultation of additional speakers in ambiguous\ncases [Q52]. The RTE dataset underwent a two-step LLM-based quality and label verification\nprocess using ChatGPT-5-Mini [Q63, Q64], with manual correction of cases where automatic\nimprovement inadvertently altered logical contradictions [Q65]. The JUDGEWEL NER dataset relied\non LLMs as judges with minimal human verification [Q37], while the Lothritz et al. NER dataset\nwas fully human-annotated [Q42]. Annotator details are limited to a brief acknowledgement of\nstudent assistants [Q114], without documentation of linguistic background or domain familiarity.\n\nFor the deployment, the annotation validity is a HIGH concern. The sentiment analysis Cohen's\nKappa of 0.45 [Q27] — moderate agreement from only two annotators — falls below standard\nreliability thresholds. No annotators are documented as having familiarity with Luxembourgish\nadministrative communication norms or civil-service registers. The LLM-assisted label\nverification for RTE [Q63, Q64] introduces uncertainty about whether labels reflect genuine\nLuxembourgish linguistic norms. The authors acknowledge that \"some annotation decisions and\nclass distributions are necessarily influenced by resource constraints\" and that \"automatic\npreprocessing may introduce biases that we cannot fully quantify\" [Q113], and flag that \"models\nmay reproduce dominant norms while under-representing regional, sociolectal, or multilingual\npractices\" [Q120].\n\n### Output Form\nAll tasks are evaluated using F1 scores [Q93, Q96]. Macro-F1 is reported for prompted LLMs\nevaluated once; encoder-based models report averaged F1 over three runs with standard deviations\n[Q96, Q89]. Class-balanced loss is applied during fine-tuning for imbalanced tasks [Q92].\nInvalid or malformed LLM outputs are discarded prior to evaluation [Q90, Q91]. Hyperparameter\nselection is performed via Bayesian search with early stopping, capped at 30 runs per\nmodel-task combination [Q138], with best hyperparameters selected on the validation set [Q137].\nFull results across validation and test sets are reported in appendix tables [Q156, Q158, Q159].\n\nFor the deployment, the output form dimension has a functional gap: the benchmark produces\nsingle-label hard classifications evaluated with F1, while the deployment operationally requires\nconfidence-scored and multi-label outputs for routing and escalation logic. The zero-shot LLM\nevaluation described [Q83, Q85] is methodologically relevant to the deployment but results\nshould be treated as indicative only due to prompt sensitivity [Q86, Q87]. The exclusive\nreliance on single-label hard F1 scoring [Q84, Q93] means the benchmark provides no calibration\ndata for the confidence-scored outputs the deployment requires.\n",
  "verbatim_quotes": [
    {
      "id": "Q1",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "This paper presents LTZGLUE, the first Natural Language Understanding (NLU) benchmark for Luxembourgish (LTZ) based on the popular GLUE benchmark for English."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q2",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Our tasks include common natural language processing tasks in binary and multi-class classification settings, including named entity recognition, topic classification, and intent classification."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q3",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We evaluate various pre-trained language models for LTZ to present an overview of the current capabilities of these models on the LTZ language."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q4",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Small and under-researched languages are particularly difficult to evaluate, as is the case with Luxembourgish (LTZ), the national language of Luxembourg, with around 400k speakers."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q5",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "LTZ only has a handful of NLU tasks available (Lothritz et al., 2022; Philippy et al., 2024; Plum et al., 2026)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q6",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "As most of these are in the news domain, and the majority of the down-stream tasks comprise less than a thousand instances, model evaluation is not always dependable."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q7",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Additional factors, such as the ongoing standardisation of the language (Gilles, 2019), vast amounts of variation (Lutgen et al., 2025), and decentralised resources, make it extremely challenging to evaluate LTZ language understanding in language models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q8",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Our contributions are: (1) LTZGLUE: the first unified GLUE benchmark for LTZ, with 8 tasks."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q9",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "(2) LTZ-E1 (mini/base): 2 new encoder language models for LTZ, which achieve competitive performance when fine-tuned on LTZGLUE."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q10",
      "page": 1,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Alistair Plum1, Felicia Körner2,3, Anne-Marie Lutgen1, Laura Bernardy1, Fred Philippy1, Emilia Milano1, Nils Rehlinger1, Cédric Lothritz4, Tharindu Ranasinghe5, Barbara Plank2,3, Christoph Purschke1 1University of Luxembourg, Luxembourg, 2LMU Munich, Germany 3Munich Center for Machine Learning, Germany 4LIST, Luxembourg, 5Lancaster University, UK"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q11",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "In this section, we introduce the eight tasks for LTZGLUE. The set spans binary and multi-class sentence and token-level classification tasks. Together, these tasks cover a broad spectrum of linguistic and semantic phenomena and provide the first unified benchmark for evaluating LTZ NLP models."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q12",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Unless stated otherwise, the textual data used across most tasks stems from two main sources: (i)"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q13",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "LTZ, the focus of this benchmark, is regarded as under-researched, and research is ongoing. Joshi et al. (2020) classify Luxembourgish as one of the \"scraping-by\" languages: although some unlabeled data exists, meaningful progress will require coordinated efforts to raise awareness and collect labeled datasets, as such resources are currently almost nonexistent."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q14",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Yet progress remains uneven across tasks, and existing resources vary widely in size, domain, and annotation quality. No unified benchmark currently exists to evaluate LTZ language understanding consistently, a gap we aim to fill."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q15",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We formulate headline acceptability (HA) as a binary classification task where the model must decide whether a given headline matches the accompanying article body."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q16",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "To construct this dataset, we use RTL news articles. We keep only documents from the twenty most frequent categories. We then filter articles by body length and title length, remove exact duplicate titles, randomly shuffle the remaining instances, and retain a fixed subset of 30k examples."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q17",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "This subset is split equally, with one half serving as the positive class with original headlines, and the other half providing the article bodies for which we assign swapped headlines."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q18",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We compute TF–IDF representations of the article texts using unigrams and bigrams, an LTZ stopword list, a minimum document frequency of two, and a large feature cap to preserve topical detail."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q19",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "For every article body in the negative half, we search its nearest neighbours to identify a donor headline, with a minimum 30-day distance so that we avoid headlines tied to the same event."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q20",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "To prevent trivial matches, we reject candidates whose headlines show high positional similarity, measured as the fraction of identical tokens in aligned positions (threshold 0.25)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q21",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We store original and swapped titles, reshuffle, and split into train (20k), development (3k), and test (6k) sets."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q22",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "The resulting negative examples remain topically related but are temporally and structurally mismatched, forcing models to attend to article content rather than surface cues."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q23",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We formulate the sentiment analysis (SA) task as a classification task where the model has to predict positive, negative, and neutral sentiment."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q24",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We use articles from RTL, randomly selected from the commentary and letter to the editor sections."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q25",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "In total, we extract 4,583 sentences, which are then annotated by two native speakers of LTZ."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q26",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Annotators are instructed to label each sentence, and to use unsure only when they would otherwise randomly use the other labels."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q27",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We calculated Cohen's Kappa at 0.45."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q28",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "For the final set, the annotators agree on a label in cases of label disagreement."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q29",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We introduce a linguistic acceptability dataset consisting of four distinct linguistic subtypes, which can either be used as a binary (LA (BINARY)) or multiclass (LA (MULTI)) classification dataset."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q30",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "The sentences are derived from the Luxembourgish Online Dictionary (LOD) and are manipulated using the tags available in the dataset."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q31",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "The first class interferes with the subject-verb agreement by changing the conjugated form of the main verb or auxiliary verb. The second class similarly modifies the declined form of the adjective and therefore violates the agreement in case, number, and gender. For the third class, we manipulate the syntax by deleting 2-3 random words from the sentence, depending on the length. The last class impacts the orthography, which is achieved by using data provided by Spellchecker.lu, a semiautomatic spellchecking website frequently used in Luxembourg. We changed one random word in the sentence by using the least frequent variant in the spellchecker data."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q32",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "The multiclass dataset and binary dataset have a 70-10-20 split, and the distribution is shown in Table 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q33",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "The binary dataset distinguishes between correct (1) and incorrect (0), for which the label 0 encompasses the categories Verb, Adj, Syntax and Ortho."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q34",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "The JUDGEWEL dataset (Plum et al., 2026) introduces an automatically constructed corpus for named entity recognition (NER) in LTZ, derived from Wikipedia and Wikidata."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q35",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Using Wikipedia's hyperlink structure, entities are matched to their corresponding Wikidata types and labelled in BIO format."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q36",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Candidate sentences are selected to maximise diversity, and a set of quality heuristics filters incomplete or overlapping entities."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q37",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "The resulting sentences are then evaluated using LLMs acting as judges, with minimal human verification to calibrate quality thresholds."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q38",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "The final dataset contains roughly 27k sentences across five entity types (see Table 3)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q39",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Models trained on JUDGEWEL achieve performance comparable to human-annotated data, demonstrating that automatically constructed resources can provide effective supervision."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q40",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "The NER dataset introduced by Lothritz et al. (2022), by contrast, is a fully human-annotated corpus derived from RTL online news comments."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q41",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "It covers a wider range of text types and registers, including informal and code-mixed writing, and focuses on four primary entity categories (PER, ORG, LOC, GPE)."
